<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <span class="section-label">The Problem</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">Knowledge trapped in thousands of merged PRs</h2>
    <p class="section-body">
      Every day, senior engineers leave high-value feedback in code review.
      That knowledge never leaves the PR thread — new hires miss it, AI
      assistants don't know it, and the same lessons get re-taught for years.
    </p>

    <div class="problem-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-card-icon">🔄</div>
        <h3>Repeated feedback</h3>
        <p>
          "Wrap this in a transaction" — same review comment, different PR,
          fifth time this month.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-card-icon">🧠</div>
        <h3>Hand-written context files</h3>
        <p>
          Teams write CLAUDE.md and .cursor/rules from memory, guessing at
          what matters.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-card-icon">🤖</div>
        <h3>AI assistants are blind</h3>
        <p>
          Copilot and Claude Code don't know your team's conventions until
          someone writes them down.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <div class="problem-card-icon">📉</div>
        <h3>Knowledge decays</h3>
        <p>
          Conventions change. Context files go stale. Nobody notices until a
          PR review surfaces the drift.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
